<br>
There have been a number of posted studies on AC and supposed caps on its effectiveness, I don't have links at hand but if you go to the usual suspects (Monkly Business, Paladins of Norrath) and hunt around they shouldn't be so tough to find.  To sum these up :-<br>
<br>
1. There is a lower and upper &quot;cap and collar&quot; on AC effectiveness.<br>
<br>
2. This *varies* with the level and (probably) ATK of the mob being fought.<br>
<br>
You can see this most easily yourself, fight a L50 mob naked, then raise your AC to around the 850 to 900AC mark.  The result?  Same damage taken.  That's because the low end for an L50 mob is somewhere around 900AC - until you get above that, adding AC is pretty meaningless. Hence Int casters who can't get a decent AC are screwed and may as well forget it when chosing equipment.<br>
<br>
The same can be seen at the top end with lower level mobs.  If you fight a L45 mob, you stop reducing damage by any meaningful amount once your AC gets past 1100.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately there don't seem to be anough studies to show just what the exact &quot;cap&quot; is for every level of mob you can encounter but it is clear that as the mob level rises so does the cap.  A test posted to Monkly Busienss last month showed than in a series of Vindicator encounters, the warrior noticed a linear decrease in damage from 1300AC through 1450AC as he continually upgraded equipment between encounters.<br>
<br>
In conclusion, actual testing shows that there is no upper limit on AC in general but there is a limit in specifics for the level (and possibly ATK) of the mobs being fought.<br>
